Regular Languages

  • A language is called a regular language if some finite automaton recognizes it
    • It is only regular iff some NFA recognizes it

Finite Automaton

  • Good for models with limited amount of memory
  • Example of a finite automaton diagram:
  • This is called a state diagram
    • It has three states, \(q_1, q_2, q_3\).
    • \(q_1\) is the starting state
    • \(q_2\) is the accept state, hence the double circle around it
    • The arrows are called transitions
  • Autamota create an output that is either accept or reject
    • The output is accept if the string ends in the accept state
      • We say that the string is accepted
  • The above state diagram reads in the following way on input string \(1101\):
  • Formal definition:
  • The formal definition of the above state diagram is as follows:
  • Say that \(A\) is a set of all of the strings that is accepted by the finite automaton (or machine) \(M\).
    • It is said that \(A\) is the language of the machine in this case and is written as \(L(M) = A\).
    • This is verbalized as \(M\) recognizes \(A\) or \(M\) accepts \(A\).
  • A machine can accept many strings but will always recognize only one language
    • A machine that accepts no strings still accepts a language, the empty language, \(\varnothing\)
  • In the above example, the language would be:
    \(A = \left\{w | w ~\text{contains at least one 1 and an even number of 0s follow the last 1}\right\}\)

Designing a Finite Automaton

  • The goal is to design a machine that will recognize the language \(L = \left\{w | w ~\text{contains an odd number of ones}\right\}~\) in the alphabet \(\Sigma = \left\{0, 1\right\}\)
  • All you need to remember is whether the number of ones seen sof ar is even or odd
    • If you read a \(1\), flip states. If you read a \(0\), stay in the same state
  • Two states needed:
  • Assign transitions by seeing how to go from one possibility to another based on reading a symbol
    • i.e.if youre in \(q_{even}\) and you read a \(1\), go to \(q_{odd}\) and vice versa
    • if youre in either state and you read a \(0\), stay there
  • Determine which will be your starting and accepting states.
    • You want to have an odd number of ones so the accept state should be \(q_{odd}\)
    • The starting state should be \(q_{even}\) because having no ones would be an even number of them.

Regular Operators

  • Like a tool for regular languages, regular operators are operations specifically designed for manipulating regular languages
  • Regular languages are defined as follows:
    • Let \(A\) and \(B\) be languages. We define regular operations union, concatenation, and star as:
      • Union: \(A \cup B = \left\{x | x \in A or x \in B\right\}\)
      • Concatenation: \(A\circ B = \left\{xy | x \in A ~\text{and}~ y \in B\right\}\)
      • Star: \(A^* = \left\{x_1x_2...x_k | k \geq 0 ~\text{and each}~ x_i \in A\right\}\)
  • Union takes all of the strings in both \(A\) and \(B\) and lumps them together into one language
  • Concatenation attaches a string from \(A\) onto the front of a string from \(B\) in all possible ways to get the strings in the new language
  • Star is a unary operation that attaches any number of strings in \(A\) together to get a string in a new language. It includes \(0\) as a possibility and the empty string \(\lambda\) is always a member of the language
  • An example of how these operators work is as follows:

Closure Under Regular Operators

  • Union: The class of regular languages is closed under the union operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages, then so is \(A_1 \cup A_2\)
    • Proof: Let \(M_1\) recognize \(A_1\) where \(M_1 = \left(Q_1, \Sigma, \delta_1, q_1, F_1\right)\) and \(M_2\) recognize \(A_2\) where \(M_2 = \left(Q_2, \Sigma, \delta_2, q_2, F_2\right)\)
      • Construct \(M\) to recognize \(A_1 \cup A_2\) where \(M = \left(Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F\right)\)
        • \(Q = \left\{(r_1, r_2) | r_1 \in Q_1 ~\text{and}~ r_2 \in Q_2\right\}\)
          This is the cartesian product of sets \(Q_1\) and \(Q_2\), written as \(Q_1 \times Q_2\). It is the set of all pairs of states, the first from \(Q_1\) and the second from \(Q_2\).
        • \(\Sigma\), the alphabet, is the same as in \(M_1\) and \(M_2\). In this theorem (and in all subsequent similar theorems) we assume for simplicity that both \(M_1\) and \(M_2\) have the same input alphabet \(\Sigma\). The theorem remains true if they have different alphabets, you would just have to modify the proff to let \(\Sigma = \Sigma_1 \cup \Sigma_2\)
        • \(\delta\), the transition function, is defined as follows:
          For each \((r_1, r_2) \in Q\) and each \(a \in \Sigma\), let
          \(\delta((r_1, r_2), a) = \left(\delta_1(r_1, a), \delta_2(r_2, a)\right)\)
          Hence \(\delta\) gets a state of \(M\) (which is actually a pair of states from \(M_1\) and \(M_2\)), together with an input symbol, and returns \(M's\) next state.
        • \(q_o\) is the pair \((q_1, q_2)\)
        • \(F\) is the set of paris in which either member is an accept state of \(M_1\) or \(M_2\). We can write it as
          \(F = \left\{(r_1, r_2) | r_1 \in F ~\text{or}~ r_2 \in F_2\right\}\)
          This expression is the same as \(F = (F_1 \times Q_2) \cup (Q_1 \times F_2)\)
    • This is the entire construction for the machine \(M\) that recognizes \(A_1 \cup A_2\)
  • Concatenation: The class of regular languages is closed under the concatenation operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages then so is \(A_1 \circ A_2\).
    • This is similar to the proof above. However, instead of constructing a machine that will accept if either \(M_1\) or \(M_2\) accept, it must accept if the input can be broken into two pieces, one of which will be accepted by \(M_1\) and the other which will be accepted by \(M_2\). The issue arises with not knowing where to break the input; we need nondeterminism to solve this (jump to NFAs).

Regular Expressions

DFAs

  • DFA stands for deterministic finite automaton
  • Has exactly one exiting transition arrow for each symbol in the alphabet and does not allow for \(\lambda\) transitions
  • The transition function takes a state and an input symbol and produces the next state

NFAs

  • NFA stands for nondeterministic finite automaton
  • In a nondeterministic machine, several choices may exist for the next state at any point
  • Compared to the automaton shown above, NFAs have additional features such as \(\lambda\) transitions, self loops, and doesnt need an arrow for each symbol in the alphabet
  • When there is an input that has multiple ways to proceed, the machine starts running all choices in parallel; each copy of the machine takes a different way to proceed
    • The splitting continues if the copy comes across another need to split
    • The copies of the machine die if there are no more options for it to proceed
    • If any of the copies accept, the entire NFA accepts
  • You can see the difference between NFAs and DFAs in a tree structure
  • The example NFA above would have a tree that looks like the following for an input string 010110
  • After analyzing the NFA, it can be seen taht it will accept all strings that contain either \(101\) or \(11\) as a substring. That is:
    \(L = \left\{w | 101 \in w ~\text{or}~ 11 \in w\right\}\)
  • It should be noted that every NFA can be converted into an equivalent DFA
    • Sometimes constructing an NFA is easier than constructing a DFA
    • For example, below is the DFA equivalent of the NFA example from above
  • Formal Definition
    • Different from a DFA in the fact that the transition function takes a state and an input symbol or the empty string and produces the set of possible next states
    • An NFA is a 5-tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F)\) where:
      • \(Q\) is a finite set of states
      • \(\Sigma\) is a finite alphabet
      • \(\delta: Q \times \Sigma_{\lambda} \to P(Q)\) is the transition function
      • \(q_o \in Q\) is the start state
      • \(F \subset Q\) is the set of accept states
    • Below is the formal definition of the above NFA example

Construct DFA from NFA

  • Consider the following NFA, \(N_4\)
  • To create a DFA, you need to know the states for the machine
    • The states will be \(P(\Sigma)\)
    • In this example, \(\Sigma = \{1, 2, 3\}\) so the DFA will have states \(\{\varnothing, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{3\}, \{1, 2\}, \{1, 3\}, \{2, 3\}, \{1, 2, 3\}\}\)
  • You need to determine the start and accept states of the DFA \(D\).
    • The starting state(s) will be those that are reachable from 1 by traveling along \(\lambda\) arrows, plus 1 itself.
      • A \(\lambda\) arrow goes from state 1 to state 3, so the starting state for \(D\) will be state \(\left\{1, 3\right\}\) (which is shown below)
    • The accepting states will be any state containing \(N_4's\) accepting state, which is state 1
      • This means that \(D's\) accepting states will be \(\{\{1\}, \{1, 2\}, \{1, 3\}, \{1, 2, 3\}\}\)
  • You can remove the unnecessary states
    • Unnecessary states are those that do not have an arrow going into them
